The Kenya Association of Pharmaceutical Industry yesterday appealed to the Pharmacy and Poisons Board to swiftly fix gaps in the drug supply chain. It said manufacturers have had to take responsibilities for poor quality of drugs reaching patients. KAPI chairperson Anastacia Nyalita said a lot of gaps within the supply chain need an urgent attention if the government intends to ensure Kenyans have access to quality and affordable medicines. Nyalita spoke during the launch of Medsource â€” a private entity seeking to promote access to affordable medication. Pharmacy and Poisons Board registrar Fred Siyoi rsaid they have made strides to regulate the safety and quality of drugs, but will look at the loopholes. Click here for the latest political news